    <section class="section">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="lead">
          <span class="eyebrow">FAQ</span>
          <h2>Plain answers before you install.</h2>
          <p>
            Sidemesh is not a cloud IDE. It is a control surface for your own
            agent hosts, which is why the host install comes first and the
            network boundary matters.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <div class="faq-row">
            <strong>Is this a hosted coding workspace?</strong>
            <p>
              No. Your code, credentials, development servers, terminals, and
              browsers stay on your own machine or VPS. Sidemesh connects to the
              daemon running next to them.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-row">
            <strong>What does the app control today?</strong>
            <p>
              Recent sessions, approvals, session chat, workspace files, git
              context, usage, hosts, terminal access, port forwarding, and
              browser previews around the agent sessions you already run
              yourself.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-row">
            <strong>Do I need the host daemon before TestFlight?</strong>
            <p>
              Yes. The mobile app becomes useful once a trusted host is
              installed, running, and reachable over the same private route as
              your device.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-row">
            <strong>Should I expose the daemon to the open internet?</strong>
            <p>
              No. Start with Tailscale, a VPN, or a trusted LAN. The daemon is
              intentionally close to powerful host capabilities, so treat it
              that way.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

